Agency Reporter  The Chief Judge of Borno, Justice Kashim Zannah, has extended the suspension of court sittings in the state to May 1, to prevent the spread of COVID-19. Zannah said this in a statement on Wednesday in Maiduguri. He said that the action was to safeguard the health and lives of litigants, staff, lawyers and judges as well as stem the spread of COVID-19 in the state. The chief judge advised judges, judicial staff and lawyers to be conscious of their responsibilities as society leaders and seek knowledge on COVID -19 only from authentic sources such as www.covid19.ncdc.gov.ng, https://edition.cnn.com/audio/podcasts/corona-virus on the pandemic. “Avoid unverified WhatsApp and other social media information because they may have fatal consequences,” Zannah said. He lauded the feat achieved in decongesting Correctional Centres thereby reducing the number of awaiting trial inmates in the state. Zannah commended the bench, bar and Civil Society Groups in the state for their steadfast and dedication to the service of humanity. (NAN)